def: Like or belonging to the Dicyemata.-- n.
Full of worth; worthy; deserving. Marston.

A flat, narrow molding, used chiefly to separate the parts ormembers of compartments or panels from one another, or doubled,turned, and interlaced so as to form knots, frets, or otherornaments. See Illust. (12) of Column.
Not sanitary; unhealthy; as, insanitary conditions of drainage.

An artificial language, intended to be universal, devised byDr. Zamenhof, a Russian, who adopted the pseudonym "Dr. Esperanto" inpublishing his first pamphlet regarding it in 1887. The vocabulary isvery largely based upon words common to the chief European languages,and sounds peculiar to any one language are eliminated. The spellingis phonetic, and the accent (stress) is always on the penult. --Es`pe*ran"tist (#), n.
An offering to a church in fulfillment of a vow.
Strong of wing; strong on the wing. [Poetic] Davies (HolyRoode).
To deprive of personality or individuality. [R.]We multiply; we dispersonate ourselves. Hare.
